                },
                {
                    "self": "https://issues.apache.org/jira/rest/api/2/issue/13226696/comment/16833719",
                    "id": "16833719",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "https://issues.apache.org/jira/rest/api/2/user?username=jorisvandenbossche",
                        "name": "jorisvandenbossche",
                        "key": "jorisvandenbossche",
                        "avatarUrls": {
                            "48x48": "https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/useravatar?avatarId=10452",
                            "24x24": "https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/useravatar?size=small&avatarId=10452",
                            "16x16": "https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/useravatar?size=xsmall&avatarId=10452",
                            "32x32": "https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/useravatar?size=medium&avatarId=10452"
                        },
                        "displayName": "Joris Van den Bossche",
                        "active": true,
                        "timeZone": "Europe/Brussels"
                    },
                    "body": "The issue here is that there is a mismatch between the pandas metadata (of the original full dataframe) and the row group:\r\n\r\n- full pandas DataFrame is converted to arrow Table, which includes this part in the metadata about the index: {code}\"index_columns\": [{\"kind\": \"range\", \"name\": null, \"start\": 0, \"stop\": 4, \"step\": 1}] {code}\r\n- the arrow Table is written to parquet as two RowGroups, but the pandas metadata is kept intact\r\n- when reading a single row group, the pandas metadata still suggest a RangeIndex of length 4, while the row group is only of length 2. As a result, a default index is used (always starting at zero, for both row groups).\r\n\r\nI am not sure this can be solved (you would need to start modifying the range start/stop values in the pandas metadata when splitting arrow tables that have such metadata. Similar issues will be encountered when eg slicing a Table). It seems the consequence of the choice to no longer serialize a RangeIndex.\r\n\r\n[~fjetter] I think the best workaround for now would be to ensure your original data has a Int64Index instead of RangeIndex, if you want to keep this working ({{df.index = pd.Int64Index(df.index)}}).\r\n\r\nGiven those issues, should we add an option to still include a RangeIndex in the actual schema? ",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "https://issues.apache.org/jira/rest/api/2/user?username=jorisvandenbossche",
                        "name": "jorisvandenbossche",
                        "key": "jorisvandenbossche",
                        "avatarUrls": {
                            "48x48": "https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/useravatar?avatarId=10452",
